    {
      "episode": 2,
      "question_num": 3,
      "question": "What is the Higgs boson and why is it important?",
      "selected_arm": "HyDE_k5",
      "method": "HyDE",
      "k": 5,
      "decision_type": "explore",
      "reward_rqm": 0.4989479124047103,
      "updated_q_value": 0.4989479124047103,
      "arm_count": 1,
      "time_seconds": 10.623878955841064,
      "hypothetical_doc": "**The Higgs boson (h)** is a fundamental scalar particle proposed to explain how elementary particles acquire mass within the Standard Model of Particle Physics. It’s not directly observed, but its existence provides crucial evidence for the Higgs field – a pervasive quantum field that interacts with other particles, giving them their masses. Without it, our understanding of fundamental forces and matter would be fundamentally incomplete.”"
    },
    {
      "episode": 2,
      "question_num": 4,
      "question": "How does general relativity describe gravity?",
      "selected_arm": "HyDE_k3",
      "method": "HyDE",
      "k": 3,
      "decision_type": "explore",
      "reward_rqm": 0.5398038045905583,
      "updated_q_value": 0.5398038045905583,
      "arm_count": 1,
      "time_seconds": 7.203159809112549,
      "hypothetical_doc": "**General Relativity – Gravity as Spacetime Curvature**\n\nEinstein’s theory posits that gravity isn't a force in the traditional sense, but rather a manifestation of spacetime curvature caused by mass and energy. Massive objects warp the fabric of space-time around them; this warping dictates how other objects move - resulting in what we perceive as gravitational attraction.  Mathematically, spacetime is described as a dynamic field influenced by matter’s density.**"
    },
    {
      "episode": 2,
      "question_num": 5,
      "question": "What is dark matter and what evidence supports its existence?",
      "selected_arm": "HyDE_k3",
      "method": "HyDE",
      "k": 3,
      "decision_type": "exploit",
      "reward_rqm": 0.5294679775347986,
      "updated_q_value": 0.5346358910626785,
      "arm_count": 2,
      "time_seconds": 6.853605270385742,
      "hypothetical_doc": "**Dark Matter:** Dark matter constitutes approximately 85% of the universe’s mass, yet remains invisible to direct observation due to its gravitational effects. Its nature is currently unknown; however, compelling evidence suggests it comprises non-baryonic dark matter particles – hypothesized to interact weakly with ordinary matter via gravity. Observations of galaxy rotation curves and gravitational lensing demonstrate a significant excess in observed mass over what can be accounted for by visible matter alone.”"
    },
