      "question": "What is the uncertainty principle in quantum mechanics?",
      "selected_arm": "HyDE_k5",
      "method": "HyDE",
      "k": 5,
      "decision_type": "explore",
      "reward_rqm": 0.4537180004273099,
      "updated_q_value": 0.47633295641601014,
      "arm_count": 2,
      "time_seconds": 6.478524923324585,
      "hypothetical_doc": "**The Uncertainty Principle**, formulated by Werner Heisenberg, fundamentally describes how accurately we can simultaneously determine certain pairs of physical properties – position and momentum, for example – within a system.  It dictates that the more precisely one property is known, the less precisely another can be determined. This inherent uncertainty arises from wave-particle duality and limits our ability to define definite values for these fundamental quantities."
    },
